 to Battle - Chapter 1 : A day in the life...</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
The day began with rain. <br>
<br>
Looking out from under the covers, in the home she and her sisters Isli and Krysta shared in Tir Na Nog, Tyl glanced out the window. <br>
<br>
Rain. <br>
<br>
Tyl seriously thought about rolling back over, pulling the sheets up, and trying to return to sleep. It's all she really did these days. Wake up, run a few errands in Tir Na Nog, wave to her acquaintances, and return home. It was the nights that haunted her. Hours spent sitting before the fireplace, watching the dance of the flames. Fatigue and sore muscles finally convincing her to retire for the night. Horrified that the next day would be just the same. <br>
<br>
And now, it was raining. <br>
<br>
Unable to fall asleep with the pouring rain beating on the roof above her head, Tyl sat up in bed. Rubbing the sleep from her eyes, she sat there, wondering how this day had arrived. THIS day. The day she swore would never come. The day she awoke without her weapons at her side. The day she found herself living a &quot;day&quot; that never changed. The &quot;day&quot; that had removed her from the harmony of life.... <br>
<br>
Such thoughts immediately sent her mind thinking to the letter. It sat there, in the corner, where it had fallen from her shaking hands that day. Hands honed to perfect balance, muscles and tendons that never flinched or moved without her explict control or reflex. Reduced to shaking... <br>
<br>
Tyl stretched out her arm, holding her hand out flat, trying to hold her hand still, to command it, to WILL it to stop.... <br>
<br>
Reduced to shaking... <br>
<br>
Tyl shook her head, trying to remove the thought from her mind, but like a moth to the light, she kept being dragged back to that moment. Even the monotony of an &quot;everyday&quot; life did not quell the memory of that day. The day the letter arrived. <br>
<br>
And now, she found herself staring at the letter. Left like a tomb by the wall, marking the end of her previous life. Everyday before (she had lost count long ago) she always walked past, with nary a glance or consicious thought. <br>
<br>
But today began with rain. <br>
<br>
Her &quot;errands&quot; would be delayed. Only the most dedicated smiths and merchants would be about this early, with pouring rain keeping their customers away. Most would remain inside, children playing games, mothers cleaning house. Warriors tending to old wounds, muscles that ached in the humidity of the downpour. Scholors reading by candlelight, mages studying or writing scrolls of spells put off for such a day as this. <br>
<br>
Tyl sat in bed, a certain dread sinking in. Tyl had no games to play, no house to clean. Her &quot;old&quot; wounds had plenty of time to heal already, her muscles actually starting to ache after a lesiurely day spent in Tir Na Nog these days. No books to read, or scrolls to study... <br>
<br>
Save one. One item, sitting across the room. A letter, resting on the floor where it was left. A tomb, the gravestone to her old life. <br>
<br>
Feeling suddenly like she was trapped, she almost bolted out of bed, and ran outside. The room had suddenly become rather sufficating. It was only rain, she told herself. It wasn't like she was UNABLE to go outside. To leave this room. To escape. <br>
<br>
Except for one problem. She had nowhere to go. <br>
<br>
As she sat there, in her bed, listening to the rain, Tyl was overcome with horror. In the silence of that moment, with her day stopped cold by a simple rain storm, she was finally made to stop. To think. To see what her life had been reduced to. <br>
<br>
Her eyes slowly followed the floor, across the room, to the letter sitting on the floor. The same place it had laid for countless days. Tyl pushed the covers of her bed aside. She walked across the room, a little more quiet than she had for the last countless days. <br>
<br>
Tyl stopped in front of the letter. Above it, on the wall, hung her blades. In the cabinet beside them rested her armor. Like a memorial, her blades glistened in the morning sunlight that had slowly peaked through the window. <br>
<br>
Tyl started to reach for the blades, hands that had been trained to intrinsically know how to hold them, suddenly unsure. Tyl stopped just inches away from the hilts, feeling the cold of the metal even at this distance. Metal grown cold like a corpse. <br>
<br>
Tyl withdrew her hand. Closing her eyes, she knelt to pick up the letter. She didn't even notice that the rain outside had stopped... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bkelrycksdaocradioandroleplaycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tylvillenria>Tyl Villenria</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#3333ff>(7/30/03 2:55 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fkelrycksdaocradioandroleplaycenterfrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=176.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Return to Battle</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Return to Battle - Chapter 2 : A Hard Day's Work...</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
&quot;What am I doing here?&quot; <br>
<br>
Tyl asked this question many times, before finally falling asleep. She had forgotten how bright the stars would shine on these summer nights, how big the moon looked when out of Tir Na Nog. How ominous the dark could be, illuminated by only a campfire. <br>
<br>
The day had started like any other day. Awaking in bed, rolling over, looking outside. And now here she was, in the wild, camping, her weapons by her side... <br>
<br>
She held them now, as she slept. Even as exhaustion over took her fears, fatigue holding court to her anxiety, her hands did not leave the hilts of her blades... <br>
<br>
Her blades. How that took getting used to again. She paused only briefly this morn when preparing her hasty departure, long enough to recognize how foreign they felt in her hands, before putting them away with the rest of her supplies. She might as well have wielded a spear, or a great sword with both hands. The effect would have been the same. <br>
<br>
And the armor! It lay beside her now, having given up the thought of sleeping in it like she used to, after a few hours of restless itching. <br>
<br>
As she slept, her thoughts and dreams went back over the course of the day... <br>
<br>
Tears, falling down... <br>
on to a letter, read only twice, in her hands. <br>
<br>
Desperation led her on, quickly grabbing her old equipment, Tyl prepared her supplies and left. (The realization that she didn't leave a note for her friends, or even for her sisters almost woke her with a start...but the day's events were too much for her weakened body). Heading out of Tir Na Nog, she was approached by a woman. She seemed familiar, but with the size of Tir Na Nog, and all of the places Tyl had been during her old career, it could well be anybody. Distress was obvious on her face, and something stirred within Tyl. Sometimes the old ways don't go away altogether. <br>
<br>
&quot;Can I help you, miss?&quot; <br>
<br>
The woman's name was Bairfhionn. Her father, a well-known bard, had gone missing. Many adventures had gone looking for him. More to move on with her business for the day, Tyl agreed to &quot;keep an eye out&quot; for him. <br>
<br>
Tyl left the city that morning, not really sure of where to go. Her immediate need was for information, but only those versed in old Elven might be of help. Perhaps it was the guilt of blowing off young Bairfhionn. Perhaps it was the &quot;justification&quot; that a renowned bard might know where to start on her new quest. Regardless of reason, Tyl decided that finding this bard was now in her best interests. <br>
<br>
Heading towards Tir Urphost, Tyl came across a guard known for having information. She asked him about the missing bard, and received directions to seek out a lurikeen near Urphost. <br>
<br>
Arriving there, Tyl found the man quite insane. Although she seemed to make out a few words from his babbling, the only ones of importance seemed to involve the missing bard, and some daemon of the air, named Aiofe. <br>
<br>
For the first time this day, Tyl asked herself, &quot;What am I doing here?&quot; <br>
<br>
A daemon?! Surely not something to be taken lightly. Tyl tried to remember all of the beasts she had defeated ago, in her &quot;old&quot; life. Many adventures came to mind, though hazy with time. She tried now to call upon those adventures, the times spent hunting with her sisters and friends. Her hands drifted to the swords on her hips, still cold. Still uninviting. <br>
<br>
As she walked away from the mad lurikeen, she drew her blades. The weight was unforgiving. She recalled the time her master had made her practice underwater, to increase her strength, and improve her response to the weight of the blades during regular sparring. The swords felt like that now. Heavy, unwieldy, foreign. <br>
<br>
Lost in thought, Tyl looked up to find herself on a hill. Glancing around, she realized she had come to the place where Aiofe was known to haunt. Waves of terror and uncertainty rolled over her now as she looked to the crest of the hill. There, in a grove of trees, stood the very daemon she was to dispatch. And it was not alone. <br>
<br>
Two huge wind spirits accompanied the daemon, one to each side. Tyl prayed that they were not together. Her heart sunk even lower when the daemon turned to leave, the two wind spirits quick to follow. <br>
<br>
Tyl kept her distance, circling around and weighing her options. Certain death. Or run away. <br>
<br>
To anyone who might have happened by at that time, the scene before them did not change. But at that moment, something occurred to Tyl. <br>
<br>
Certain death, or run away? <br>
<br>
Tyl thought back over the weeks spent in Tir Na Nog, her love of life drained from her being, as one day flowed into the next, one day into a week, a week into a month. There was no telling how much time had passed in that room within their house in Tir Na Nog. <br>
<br>
Certain death, or run away? <br>
<br>
The words echoed in her mind, their meaning slowly becoming clear to her.... <br>
<br>
Certain death, or certain death? <br>
<br>
It was the same. No, it wasn't. At least with one of those choices, she would die doing what she loved.... <br>
<br>
Tyl slowly stood, her blades already in her hands, as if by magic. Suddenly, they didn't feel quite as cold, not quite so heavy. Not quite so foreign... <br>
<br>
Right now, they felt like she had come home. <br>
<br>
Sprinting across the field, Tyl bared down on the three spirits. Her approach did not go unnoticed, and the three turned to meet her rush. The wind spirits moved to stop her, but Tyl's vision was centered on one adversary, one goal. Splitting the two beasts, Tyl ran, hardly feeling as their claws ripped against her armor, hardly feeling the first attack of magic from the daemon Aiofe. <br>
<br>
A scream, feral and passionate, filled the air as Tyl cried out. Not in pain, but in pure battle rage. Unleashing her pent up feelings, those of uncertainty and distress, Tyl's spirit was a force itself against Aiofe, appearing to anyone who might have happened by at that time as a glowing sword, the swordmaiden's essence. <br>
<br>
Had Tyl been aware of what was happening around her, she would have known that she was in serious trouble. Her burst of energy was fading fast, the blades in her hands growing heavier, as blow after blow was rained down on her from behind by the two wind spirits. All of this went unnoticed to Tyl, though, fully taken over by the flow of the battle. With her last bit of strength, Tyl thrust forward with both blades, stealing the last bit of essence from the daemon Aiofe. The daemon was banished back to its plane, leaving behind a small vial containing the essence of its corporal form. Tyl reached forward, grabbing the vial and pulling it close to her body as the last blow landed on her beaten body. <br>
<br>
Mercifully, Tyl passed out. She didn't even feel the wind spirits continue their onslaught, finally leaving her when it seemed she was finally dead. <br>
<br>
To anyone who might have happened by at that time, they would be witness to a rare thing. Something that hadn't happened in countless months... <br>
<br>
Tyl smiled. <br>
