<br>
Connla was a small town. Although it had grown since the founding of Howth, and the new activity farther south in Innis Carthaig, Connla continued to have the flavor of a border town. Many adventurers grew up in Connla these days, fed countless stories as children by the men and women who stopped in town for supplies. Children who dreamed of adventure beyond the hills of Connla. <br>
<br>
With all of the coming and going everyday by the adventurers of the realm, it should come as no surprise that no one marked the day when he arrived. <br>
<br>
It was also not a coincidence that the stranger blended in. His hair, although bright red, was styled in the fashionable celtic manner, with short little spikes. His clothes were non-descript, with just a light blue cloak to contrast his drab leather jerkin. He took special care not to glance about too much. Enough to be mistaken for a traveler's first visit to Connla, but not enough to stand out from the others. His voice was deep and rich, befitting his cover as a wandering bard, but he kept his words short, and to the point. Although he hardly noticed, his accent was still faintly there, enough for the first few people he encountered from the surrounding area to take an interest in where he had come from... <br>
<br>
Questions he was not ready to answer just yet. <br>
<br>
The stranger smiled as he walked into Connla that day. Such a simple town, full of life. Children ran by, off to the nearby forest. He faintly heard one of them proclaim the day's game to be tree-climbing. A good-natured smirk found it's way on the stranger's face, as he neared the center of town. <br>
<br>
However, it did not stay. Hibernia was a large country, with many forests, both deep and foreboding. Finding the right one would be a challenge for the stranger. With no friends, no money, and only a vague memory of the place he sought, the task seemed impossible. <br>
<br>
But then, his family said the same thing back home about him actually getting to Hibernia. And here he was. <br>
<br>
Connla, the home of adventurers. <br>
<br>
The stranger gathered with the other travelers that night, by the bonfire near the river. He slipped out of most questions about his own travels, his ability to get people to talk honed sharp from years of diplomatic meetings in his homeland. Soon enough, everyone had told their story in turn, before finally retiring for the night. He listened intently to each one, hoping to hear some clue, hoping to hear the name. The name of the one he desperately seeked. <br>
<br>
Finally alone by the fire that first night in Connla, the stranger whispered into the night: <br>
<br>
&quot;I'll find you Vencklayne, no matter where you hide. You have quite a bit of explaining to do, old friend...&quot;  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bkelrycksdaocradioandroleplaycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tylvillenria>Tyl Villenria</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#3333ff>(7/30/03 2:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fkelrycksdaocradioandroleplaycenterfrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=176.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Return to Battle</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Return to Battle - Chapter 4 : The Good Ole Days...</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>The young girl bent down, picking up yet another wayward arrow. This made the eighteenth one. She only needed to find the last two, then it would be time for dinner. Plenty of time in fact. Today most of the arrows actually went in the same general direction, and she had found many of them stuck into this or that tree. Still, she had a lot to learn. The last arrow she found was sixty yards behind the target. <br>
<br>
She began to wonder again why the master was so particular about finding all of the arrows. She had seen him make them from old twigs, found all over the forest where they lived. Certainly it was not for fear of running out. Was it for the sake of secrecy? She had never seen another person near their forest. The only people she ever saw were from a distance, on the few trips the master had taken her out of the forest. Those trips, like everything else, centered around learning. The master would point out this or that shape across a wide field, usually on horseback on a dusty dirt road. The words &quot;Celt&quot;, &quot;Firbolg&quot;, and &quot;Lurikeen&quot; were taught to her at an early age. She always wondered why they never came across any &quot;Elves&quot;. Elves were her favorite. The master had many books on Elven Lore, and after learning to read and write, she begged him to allow her to read them all. He smiled at her then, knowing that at her young age, she could not imagine the sheer number of books he owned about that topic. <br>
<br>
But then again, when you live to be several hundred years old, you tend to collect a few classics. <br>
<br>
Still, even he was impressed with her tenacity. Every few days, she would return to his study, trying to balance the tomb on her back, taking care not to drag the heavy book across the ground. He jokingly asked her one night if she could possibly show this much enthusiasm towards her archery lessons. With the sincerity of a child, she replied that the arrows were there every day. The bow, the target, the trees; all of these things never changed. But the stories of Elven Lore were unique. Each one a lesson in itself. Even after untold centuries, mysteries were still being found, places unexplored, creatures never seen by mortal man continued to live, to reproduce, to thrive...untouched for eons. Smiling at her innocence in taking his comment seriously, he handed her a new book. This one was rather threadbare, as if it had been studied numerous times, cross-referenced with other documents, marked and eared for particular chapters of interest. <br>
<br>
On it's cover read the words: <br>
<br>
&quot;Beyond the veil, an anthology of the known information about the lands outside our home.&quot; <br>
<br>
The girl ran off eagerly, ready to dive into this new story. As she left, the master paused in his own studies, wondering if he was doing the right thing. Wondering if he hadn't just planted the seeds to a horrible future, a fate his student might not be ready to handle.... <br>
<br>
The girl shook her head, remembering that she still had to find two more arrows before supper. Still taking her time, picking through the underbrush, she spotted number nineteen. At this rate, she may have just enough time to read another chapter before dinner. With this thought in mind, she eagerly set to the task at hand....</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> <br>
<br>
&quot;That was a fasicnating story. Truely you do your profession justice. Might I ask your name?&quot; <br>
<br>
The bard smiled, &quot;Of course young man. I am Amargein, a bard of little fame. And you?&quot; <br>
<br>
The stranger smirked, though it was difficult to see this night. His light blue cloak wrapped close from the cool night, and the shadows from the fire thrown strategically across his face hid much from Amargein. <br>
<br>
&quot;A fellow bard, of no repute. But before I forget, I couldn't help but notice that you did not use any names in your story. Was this purposeful, by chance, or have the names faded with the telling?&quot; <br>
<br>
Amargein the bard paused. The stranger tried to remain calm, but even he could tell that this man was suddenly on his guard, quietly trying to see beyond the shadows covering the strangers face. The bards eyes, old but intense, bore holes through the stranger's dark shroud. A flicker, just now! Recognition? <br>
<br>
Impossible, thought the stranger. No one on this land knew of him. Or perhaps the old bard suddenly recognized that this was no simple telling of a tale to a hapless young country bard... <br>
<br>
The stranger smiled slyly as the old bard began to speak again, &quot;Well, that was many years ago, decades even. I barely remember the tale, actually. I'm afraid I can not recall anything more about it.&quot; <br>
<br>
Finality. It dripped off his words to the stranger, one who had made a living by reading his opponents words, or more importantly, the way they said them. He would gather no more information from this one. <br>
<br>
The stranger stretched, letting a yawn out to distract the bard as his hand flexed next to his dagger, hidden underneath his cloak. There was a chance that this old bard might now know too much. Bards were rather tricky to deal with anyway, and having one as old as this, who clearly had been rattled by the strangers questions...this bard might not easily &quot;forget&quot; the strangers passing. <br>
<br>
The stranger smiled again. No. There was no need at the moment. He glanced over at the bard's makeshift hut. This man was not going anywhere soon. And the stranger had tapped this locale dry for rumors and stories. It was time to move on, farther north. <br>
<br>
It was time to find more adventurers, more people that were still connected with the everyday events of this realm. <br>
<br>
It was time to visit Tir Na Nog.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#A0B0E0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bkelrycksdaocradioandroleplaycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tylvillenria>Tyl Villenria</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#3333ff>(7/30/03 3:00 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fkelrycksdaocradioandroleplaycenterfrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=176.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Return to Battle</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Chapter 5: Renewal, a vow kept</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>The master opened the door, beckoning for her to go inside. The young woman paused just long enough, showing the respect for this day. Nothing was announced between them, but she knew something different was happening today. This room had remained closed ever since she could remember. It had been nine years since she began her lessons with the bow. It had not been going well. <br>
<br>
She had improved, to be sure. Just yesterday, she had only missed one shot. Four had been direct bull’s-eyes. However, she could tell in the way the master looked on, even this was not good enough. Not good enough for him. She had no idea what he thought of that night of her improvement. She arrived at her spot for morning practice, only to find the master already there. This in itself was strange, as he normally allowed her to practice alone, only coming by for the days challenges. But not today. <br>
<br>
He merely told her to practice, to gather her arrows when finished, and to meet him here, during their normally planned archery time. <br>
<br>
From within the room, a soft light flowed out. The young woman was momentarily surprised, sensing correctly that this room had been closed for years, at least as long as she could remember. There was no telling when someone had last stepped through the door... <br>
<br>
And now she stepped through, to find a small room. From either side, doorways led off to small alcoves. The master beckoned her to go inside. <br>
<br>
The weapons lined the walls. The alcove was covered in them, of all shapes and sizes. And not one had a bit of dust. Sensing that something was very strange here, the young woman barely heard the noise coming from the main room. <br>
<br>
Standing in the middle of the room, the master held two blades, looking right at the young woman. <br>
<br>
&quot;You reached your full potential with the bow I'm afraid&quot;, he said. &quot;It's time now to see if blades are more to your liking.&quot; <br>
<br>
The young girl grabbed two weapons, the closest she found. They seemed cold, unwieldy, foreign. <br>
<br>
The master smiled briefly, sheathing one of his swords, and placing it to the side. <br>
<br>
&quot;Why don't we start with the basics? Two blades can be very difficult to wield, even for dexteritous elves like myself. We will have plenty of time to work up to two.&quot; <br>
<br>
The master chuckled, trying his best to hide the slight cough that had overcome him. He honestly wondered if there would be enough time. He honestly hoped there would. He had a vow to keep. He looked back to his student. <br>
<br>
His last student. <br>
<br>
The master began his lesson. &quot;In sword fighting, there are only five main styles...&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> <br>
<br>
Tyl awoke, shaking the remaining thoughts from her morning daze. Her body ached all over. She looked down to find blood caked on her armor. Her blood. The images of her battle with the wind spirits flooded back to her, while her body seemed to take advantage of this to remind her just how badly it was beaten. Tyl felt dizzy, but knew it was best to stand, to fight her way to focusing again. Waves of nausea rolled through her head as she came to her feet. She looked about, trying to place where she was. <br>
<br>
The hill. It appeared she had rolled down the hill, and had been left for dead. She glanced down, to the object still in her grasp. The vial appeared to be safe. It was time to return to the mad little lurikeen. <br>
<br>
It was only after the day’s travels, first to the lurikeen who helpfully directed her to find the hometown of the missing bard, and then to the south, and the little hut where the bard Amargein now lived, that Tyl began to wonder just what had happened. Here she was, in her armor, with her blades, riding across the countryside. Being an adventurer. It seemed so natural. But perhaps it was only because Tyl did not know what else to do. She still needed to ask this bard about the old Elven Lore. She hoped he might know the answer she seeked, or at least, where she might find someone who did. <br>
<br>
Amargein appeared a little troubled today, taken by surprise at having her as a visitor. He calmed noticeable when Tyl showed him the essence of Aiofe, and gave him the note from his daughter in Tir Na Nog. He hastily wrote a note in reply, asking if Tyl might be headed that way. The bard had a lot of work to do, to collect his things and leave the hut. <br>
<br>
Tyl agreed, asking only if she may ask the bard a question in return. She wondered how to phrase her question, not really sure herself what it was. In the end, she simply asked, &quot;I'm looking for someone that might know about very old Elven Lore. A book, to be precise.&quot; <br>
<br>
Amargein paused briefly, a strange look crossing his face for an instant, too fast for Tyl to take notice, as he quickly began to speak. <br>
<br>
&quot;I'm afraid I don't, milady. But for matters of old, your best bet might be to try the city of Caille. It is quite close to the Empyreans own home. Both them and the inhabitants of Caille are known for their magical roots, and many scholars go there to study such things.&quot;, Amargein said. <br>
<br>
Tyl thanked the bard, returning to Tir Na Nog long enough to give his note to his daughter. Gathering some more supplies, she headed out to Caille, hoping that there someone might have heard about the book. <br>
<br>
Tyl was sure the book would have the information she seeked. Information to help make sense out of that damn letter. Information to help her decide her course of action, hopefully before it was too late. <br>
<br>
Tyl knew of only two people to have read that book. One was an old elven teacher, who passed away many years ago. The other was lost to her now, gone in the haze of distant pasts, who only read the book for the storytelling itself anyway. She only remembered the title: <br>
<br>
