<br>
Tyl rode into Caille, and immediately noticed the silence. Most towns in Hibernia were border towns, on the outskirts of the capital, and surrounded by danger. Because of this, they were usually busy with guards patrolling, adventurers purchasing their supplies, hunting parties coming in and preparing to leave. Caille was not like the other towns of Hibernia, although it was not located at any safer region within the realm. <br>
<br>
Tyl dismounted her horse, and noticed that there were no stables in town. She sent her horse onward to Druim Cain, knowing that it was familiar enough with the route to safely traverse the danger. Turning about and facing the town itself, she immediately saw that this was not going to be easy. <br>
<br>
Doors closed just beyond her sight as she turned around, people running from the open road to safety inside unmarked buildings. Those townsfolk that did remain outside and in view stared quietly at Tyl, watching every move she made. These were the merchants, the ones that tolerated the unannounced visits of strangers, knowing a profit was to be made. A few were not even from this strange town, but had come here to make their fortune. <br>
<br>
This was not Tyl’s first visit to Caille, but every time she stopped here it unnerved her just the same. She felt as if she had just walked into someone else’s wedding party. A wedding party, or a funeral. It did not matter, the feeling was the same. Unwanted, unknown, unwelcome. <br>
<br>
There was one man still in town that she did know, a young merchant that she had helped many months ago. She looked for him now, amongst the other shopkeepers. Spotting him, she noticed a brief flash of recognition from him. Without a word, he turned and walked towards the edge of town. <br>
<br>
Tyl followed the young man, quietly, respecting the ways of this small town, even if she did not understand them. Having moved away from the others, the young man finally turned about. <br>
<br>
“What is it?” <br>
<br>
Tyl looked on dumbfounded, and a little taken aback. The tone was obviously one of impatience, with a hint of resignation. <br>
<br>
“I…I need information”, Tyl stammered. <br>
<br>
“I’m afraid you’ve come to the wrong town then. We keep to ourselves. We don’t keep track of what’s going on in that world out there, and frankly, we like it that way,” the young man quickly replied. <br>
<br>
“I need to know about the elves. The elves of old”, Tyl said, desperation seeping into her voice. <br>
<br>
The young man paused, appearing to be lost in thought. Finally, he spoke, turning to leave. <br>
<br>
“I can’t help you. No one in this town can. You’re only hope would be to speak with the Watchers, outside of town. They are the empyreans that live nearby. You should find them easily enough.” <br>
<br>
And with that, the young man left, returning to town, and refusing to even look at Tyl again. <br>
<br>
Tyl left Caille, knowing exactly where these Watchers lived. She had previously dealt with them on one occasion, involving a man from her own hometown…. from Connla. He had been a watcher as well, though his actions had banished him from living in Bri Leith with the other Watchers. <br>
<br>
Tyl hoped that they remembered her. <br>
<br>
The blademaiden walked through the valley, leading to the home of the Watchers. She looked about the valley, seeing that more and more of the watchers were marking her passage, but none moved to stop her. As she approached the chieftess, Tyl began to wonder exactly what she could say, how she could explain to these beings, these ghosts, that she needed their help. And why would they even bother to help one not of their race, when Tyl herself had seen the consequences in the form of the man who now resided in Connla? <br>
<br>
These thoughts were quickly brushed from her mind, completely surprised, and a little scared, when the chieftess spoke first: <br>
<br>
“Tyl Villenria. I’ve been waiting for you.”<br>
