<br>
The stranger entered the city, taken aback by its size. Carved within a mountain, the bard expected to see the inside created by the hands like that of a dirty dwarf, or a kobold. However, once he passed the capital’s gates, he saw that he was mistaken. <br>
<br>
Carved would not seem to be the right word for the magic of this place. Torn asunder would be more appropriate. The stranger looked about, seeing the inside of the mountain itself had been ripped apart from the base, almost as if a god had reached down and touched the very core. The stranger knew that this realm was full of magic, but even he was not prepared for such a mighty show of force. For the first time, the stranger did feel a little uncomfortable; hoping beyond hope that those responsible for this feat of ability had long ago passed away, and had taken the secrets of this lands magic with them. <br>
<br>
Not wanting to waste any more time in this city then he needed to, the bard made haste to the castle itself. Barely having time to take in the sights, the sounds, the people, he entered the courtyard to the capital, and hoped to find someone who could get him an audience with the king. It wasn’t until he realized that people weren’t paying any attention to him (or at least, the amount of attention that he was hoping for), that he recognized a rather peculiar situation. The king’s outer chambers were all guarded by elves. The place was surrounded with them! The stranger had never seen one up close…. well, only one so long ago…and had very limited knowledge of their abilities and demeanors. Save for one fact that he remembered quite well from his past. They were not susceptible to charms. <br>
<br>
Quietly leaving the castle walls, the stranger found a small tavern, and weighed his options. As he brought his first drink to his lips, he gazed across the room, suddenly sensing an opportunity he could not pass up. <br>
<br>
Just as he was well versed in the innate abilities of elves to ward against charms, the bard also knew how to recognize when someone not only lacked these defenses, but also was more naturally susceptible. That someone sat across the room to him now. <br>
<br>
She was a young Celt, with long dark hair. Her face had the blue ink markings that were popular with the warriors of the day, and she carried an assortment of weapons with her. Even as she sat in the tavern, quietly sipping her drink, the stranger could sense that she did not feel comfortable. Her interactions with the staff, along with her desire not to make eye contact with any of those sitting near her table led the bard to recognize this one’s most immediate traits. Shy, unsure, wanting to be accepted by her peers. <br>
<br>
A slow smile found its way to the strangers face. <br>
<br>
Later that day, as he was counting his full coin purse and polishing his new armor and weapons, he wondered if perhaps there was more opportunity to be had with this young girl. Looking over his new magical trinkets, he thought surely someone who had acquired such powerful items belonged to a guild that was quite powerful, and willing to help any who called one of them friend. A network of travelers such as that might be useful in his search for Vencklayne. Or at least, make his stay in Hibernia a little more comfortable. <br>
<br>
Yes, this band of travelers, this Fellowship of Dihn, could prove quite useful…and with the word of the heroine Shaenon as introduction, should not pose much trouble to infiltrate. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bkelrycksdaocradioandroleplaycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tylvillenria>Tyl Villenria</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 8<br> <font color=#3333ff>(7/30/03 3:04 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fkelrycksdaocradioandroleplaycenterfrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=176.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Return to Battle</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Chapter 8: Adventure awaits!</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <br>
<br>
The stranger awoke in his room in Tir Na Nog. Though staying inside the city had its distinct troubles, he enjoyed being in touch with what was going on. It was also his chance to find out more information on Vencklayne, and possibly his whereabouts. <br>
<br>
Before the bard could prepare to leave for the day’s visit to the merchants’ center, he received word from the young Shaenon. It appeared that two young members of her guild were out hunting, and would not turn away another of their season. She wondered if the stranger would be able to assist them. <br>
<br>
Seeing no time like the present to familiarize himself with the members of this guild, he decided to accept the invitation. Leaving the gates of Tir na Nog behind, he came across a young elven lass. Though young in appearance, it was apparent to the shrewd bard that this one had wisdom beyond even her elven years, and should not be trifled with. As he approached, he sensed that even now, she was on her guard. No word from a young Celt heroine would simply dissuade her from her suspicions. With a smile, he greeted her, hoping to keep the mood light, and distract her from any of the numerous questions he believed to be running around in her head. <br>
<br>
“Greetings m’lord”, the elven lady said. “I hear you know Shaenon.” <br>
<br>
The stranger took pause. A tone in her voice….distrust, curiosity, disdain, relief? These elves were ever a problem to deal with. <br>
<br>
“Aye, m’lady” <br>
<br>
“Well then, I am Lysaria. It will be a pleasure to hunt with you, being a friend of Shaenon. And your name, m’lord?” <br>
<br>
<br>
“Brendyn. Just, Brendyn,” he replied. <br>
<br>
“Well, m’lord Brendyn, there are a few friends meeting us here, and then we will be off.” <br>
<br>
A soft chuckle escaped the air nearby, as a short lurikeen came into view. Brendyn sighed quietly, beginning to wonder just how this situation could get any worse. Though his knowledge of elves was limited, he only knew a little more about lurikeens. And what he did know, he didn’t like. The size of a small child, and just as mischievous, lurikeens had about half the resistance to magic as elves, but twice the suspicion of being tricked. Tricksters were always the hardest to dupe, always looking for their own chance to take advantage of a situation. This made most of Brendyn’s charms practically impossible to use. <br>
<br>
As the two ladies greeted each other, Brendyn weighed his options. Just as he felt like he had control of the situation before him, he saw him. A huge, towering creature approached from the east. Brendyn’s hand hovered near his blade, though he relaxed a little when his companions waved and smiled to the giant. As he approached, Brendyn could not help but groan audibly, his hand moving to his head instead. A Firbolg. Creatures more attune to nature than even the elves, and this one a druid no less. One in harmony with his surroundings would know immediately if something was amiss with his companions, striking down every last hope Brendyn had of using the situation to his advantage today. He finally decided that he would just have to rely on his natural charisma, and hope that he was able to at least win over a few of them this day. <br>
<br>
The young Lurikeen was Lynna, a ranger. One who happened to enjoy hiding in shadows almost as much as a rogue. The giant Firbolg was introduced as Sleiyn, a gentle druid, who offered his blessings to the group as they prepared to move out to hunt. Although Sleiyn would not be joining them today, Brendyn was taken aback by his power, and thought it wise not to do anything too brash while traveling with the ladies. He did not like his chances alone against this druid standing before him, and had a feeling he would immediately figure out any enchantments the bard might try on the young women. <br>
<br>
The three set out, hunting the wildlife around a few of the merchant towns south of Tir na Nog. While most of their time was spent quietly stalking their prey, Brendyn did manage to engage them in a limited discussion. He also studied their tactics carefully, in the event that one day he found himself on the battleground against these formidable foes. And formidable they were. The ranger Lynna was deadly with her bow, choosing a few targets that she felled before they arrived to her, before Brendyn could even lend a hand to the combat. And the nightshade Lysaria, always hiding in shadows, awaiting the prey to walk into their trap. Both Lysaria and Lynna spent more time hiding then in plain sight, leaving Brendyn feeling alone more and more during the course of their time together. <br>
<br>
As their hunt came to a close, Brendyn took his leave, returning to his room in Tir na Nog. He had much to think about. He was impressed with the members of Dihn he had come across today. Though they ranged in race, profession, and season, they seemed to have built a bond beyond those simple labels. He thought that their guild was more like a family to many of them, and not just a collection of travelers following the same path. Something about that called out to Brendyn, so far away from home and loved ones. He almost felt sorry about using them strictly for finding Vencklayne…. <br>
<br>
Vencklayne, the name jarring him from his contemplation… <br>
<br>
He almost felt sorry for them…. <br>
<br>
Almost.<br>
