<br>
“Tyl Villenria, I’ve been waiting for you.” <br>
<br>
The chieftess stood before Tyl, unmoving. Tyl could only look back, stunned by the recognition being bestowed to her by the empyrean leader. <br>
<br>
“We haven’t much time. I’ve been asked to direct you towards your goal, to the book you seek. Your answers do indeed lie within its cover. <br>
<br>
“The book you seek lies deep within the tomb of the Muire family. Although many raiders have pillaged the tomb over the decades since it’s placement there, the book itself is old and non-descript, a threadbare collection of old stories. It is quite possible that it has been untouched all these years. <br>
<br>
“However, you are not the only one who seeks the knowledge held within. As we speak, another approaches the tomb of Muire. You must make haste there, and acquire the book first.” <br>
<br>
As she finished, the chieftess pointed towards the west. Tyl took her cue, jogging off towards Druim Cain. Towards the horse that would return her to Muire Tomb. <br>
<br>
Muire Tomb. <br>
<br>
As Tyl ran up the hill leading to the tomb entrance, she recalled the times she had spent there as a young warrior. That place was filled with memories, many of them before she met her friends, Anam na Eireann and the Fellowship of Dihn. Before she had met her sisters. <br>
<br>
Save one memory, the one that came to mind now as she stood there, at the stairway leading down into the tomb. Her hand brushed the stone wall, recalling her last expedition into the tomb, one she has shared with her sisters. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>“I vow never to return to this tomb. My journeys here are finished for all time.”</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> <br>
<br>
Tyl paused at the entrance, conflicted with emotions. A vow was not something to be taken lightly. And yet, here lies the resting place of the tomb she seeked. <br>
<br>
Tyl was drawn out of her internal debate by the sounds of someone approaching through the forest behind her. Quickly, she found some underbrush, and looked on. <br>
<br>
Something about this seemed too familiar. Suddenly, she remembered: <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>A human! The little girl had nearly dropped her bow. She had never seen one before in the master’s forest. Hiding beneath the underbrush, she watched as this brave soul wandered deeper into the foreboding forest. No one had ever made it this deep, with the forest magically darkened to prevent intruders. She watched as the man stumbled around, obviously lost. Then, she saw it. <br>
<br>
A wolf, possibly the largest she had ever seen, stalking the human. It was clear that the wolf had followed him in, perhaps even forcing him to find shelter within the forest. <br>
<br>
The girl was at a loss. The master had taught her the sanctity of life, never to attack the animals, teaching her the ways of avoidance, of recognition. He told her that fighting the animals of the land was not a challenge with her skills, not even sport. <br>
<br>
But it was also apparent that the human, although unwanted and unwelcome in their forest, would not make it out alive. The wolf had already found the human, and was setting up for its strike. <br>
<br>
The little girl closed her eyes, not wanting to see the gruesome demise of the human. <br>
<br>
To the human in the forest, nothing had changed, only the sound like that of an insect buzzing by, barely breaking the threshold of his senses. <br>
<br>
The little girl opened her eyes, familiar with the sound of her master’s arrow flying through the air. There, where the beast was about to make its leap, lay the dead wolf. It’s life ended swiftly with a perfectly aimed arrow. <br>
<br>
They trailed the human, master and student, making sure he found his way out without incident. The little girl wanted desperately to question her master about today’s activities, but knew she would not learn anything until they arrived back at their home. <br>
<br>
As the day ended, she finally asked, “Master, why did you kill the wolf? I thought you took a vow never to kill the animals of the forest?” <br>
<br>
The master looked at his student, a bit surprised by her thoughtfulness. “My child, vows are important things, not to be broken lightly. However, we are not bound to one vow alone. There are some vows that are more important than others, and when two vows conflict, it is best to be sure not to break the more important vow by keeping the lesser. Had I not killed the wolf, I would have kept that vow. Yet there is a vow more important that I have made: To protect the weak, those who cannot fight for themselves. My actions today do not speak of the worthlessness of my vow to not kill the animals. They speak of the worth of my vow to protect the weak, even at the expense of my word.”</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Tyl, her concerns set to rest, smiled as she entered the tomb. Not from any joy in breaking her vow to never return to the crypt, but from the assurance brought to her of the importance of this task. The lesser of two vows would be broken, offered as sacrifice to secure the more important vow. A personal vow, one that must be accomplished at all cost. For Tyl’s sake. For the memory of her Master. <br>
<br>
The sounds of battle flowed from the bottom of the stairs, a cry for help above the tumultuous collection of combat. Pulling her blades free, Tyl ran the rest of the way down, any thought of her vow gone with the call for help in her ears.<br>
