<br>
Tyl entered the intersection, moving her torch left and right. It had been many seasons since she had last been within the tomb of Muire, yet the layout came back to her quickly. Many months had been spent searching for treasure and fighting the beasts that had come to call the dank corridors home. Ghosts and ghouls remained to protect the sacred halls, rising even now to guard the tombs from being spoiled. Having no need to search for the lost weapons and armors of such a long ago past, Tyl moved on. She had only one item in mind, a book from her past. One that promised to hold the answers she seeked. <br>
<br>
Tyl turned to leave, seeking the lower room with the spirit of Beare Muire, the family’s sworn protector, and unofficial queen of the tomb. However, before she moved on, Tyl felt a cold wind blow through behind her. It came from a room Tyl had known well. That room was a favorite hunting ground, with many spirits rising up to fight off the multitude of young heroes who sought the riches of the upper floors. <br>
<br>
Something didn’t seem right though, for Tyl had never encountered a breeze from that side of the tomb. In fact, there was only one exit from the tomb, and that hall alone had been the only home to such breezes, however weak. In every other room, the air hung thick with decay and mold. Yet here, a floor below and a hall away, a breeze did flow….and it flowed out of the room she now turned to look into. <br>
<br>
Tyl approached, for the first time in a long time, trepidation entering her steps. <br>
<br>
As she rounded the corner, Tyl saw the broken wall. And beyond, spiraling stairs lead down, guarded by three skeleton warriors. The bones looked brittle and old, yet the bodies moved up and down, as if still trying to draw in breath. Their skinny hands held weapons glowing with magic, as each of the three heads turned to look at her. <br>
<br>
Tyl waited, as each side gauged the strength of the other. With no approach, Tyl breathed a little easier. Perhaps these guardians of the tomb knew she was only here for one thing, and that item did not belong to the Muire family. Perhaps they were equally intimidated by Tyl’s warrior spirit as she was of their dedication to protect what was theirs. Perhaps it was something completely beyond her perception. In any case, Tyl walked past, shivering as she felt their empty eye sockets focusing on her every move. <br>
<br>
Reaching the bottom of the stairs, Tyl felt the breeze continue past her and up the stairs. A little stronger, a little cleaner. There must be another entrance near by. Tyl continued down the hall, passing numerous skeleton warriors, a few wearing the tattered armor signifying them as champions in the order. Tyl shivered again, thinking of the magical prowess within the spirits of the undead champions required to bring them back to serve their family, years, decades even, after their death. <br>
<br>
Ahead Tyl found another set of stairs spiraling down, yet the hallway continued forward. A slight breeze came from ahead. Pulling her cloak around her, she followed the clean air, and walked forward through the doorway ahead. <br>
<br>
Tyl entered a huge, circular room. Looking around, she saw that she was actually on the second floor of the room, standing on a small ledge that circled the dais below. Glancing down, Tyl felt the energy before she even saw her. <br>
<br>
Tyl was wrong. Beare Muire was not the queen of the tomb. She didn’t even belong to the royal family, compared to the strength, the hatred, that emanated from below. <br>
<br>
The true Queen had awaked, and she was not pleased with the state of her tomb. <br>
<br>
Finally tearing her eyes away from the majesty of the queen, Tyl saw the immediate source of her ire. Near a set of stairs going up, a young warrior, his black cloak tight about his body, appeared to be deciding whether making the trip this deep was worth the anger of the royal family. As the warrior stood, transfixed, the queen’s mummified handmaidens began their approach, somehow pushing words from their decayed bodies, their wrapped hands forming magical symbols. They would not allow this fool to desecrate their queen’s resting place. <br>
<br>
Tyl jumped down from the ledge, landing between the handmaidens and the unlucky warrior, and unsheathed her blades before thought had formed action. <br>
<br>
“Run away, and run fast…or they will overcome you!”, Tyl shouted…hoping the young warrior still had time to escape. <br>
<br>
The young warrior slowly smiled, giving a slight bow to this brave warrior maiden, before deftly throwing his cloak over his shoulders. There, under his arm, was a book. Old and threadbare, it would be undistinguishable to any who did not specifically seek it out. <br>
<br>
Tyl stood perfectly still, completely shocked. <br>
<br>
The young warrior, a grin from ear to ear now on his face, raised a hand to his brow. With a quick salute and a wink, the man turned and ran up the stairs…stairs where a gust of fresh air freely flowed. The source of the fresh air throughout this side of the tomb. <br>
<br>
The exit to the outside world. <br>
<br>
Tyl didn’t even feel the first spell shock her body, staring as she was at the exit of the cloaked rogue. The blast from the second spell was still harder to notice, matched with the sound of a cave in from atop the stairs. <br>
<br>
A scream filled the room, overpowering even the queen who was in the throws of her own spell casting. The four of them, handmaidens and queen, stared at Tyl. Her eyes closed, face set in a grimace, she turned back to face the undead before her. <br>
<br>
“I guess you’re not going to let me just walk out of here, huh? At least your bodies will not feel the pain of my blades. Rest in peace, Lady Muire” <br>
<br>
