<br>
The vase shattered against the wall, frightening the few birds that had gathered at the inn’s window. Brendyn sat down on the bed in disgust. Months had passed since his arrival to Hibernia, and he was no closer to finding Vencklayne. The days began to drag by, each as disappointing as the last. No record of his name, no record of his coming and going, no family or friends. It seemed that Vencklayne had disappeared off the face of the realm. <br>
<br>
Brendyn worried, and not for the first time, that something more insidious might have happened to Vencklayne. He shook his head, clearing such thoughts. Vencklayne was a crafty one, to be sure. Brendyn doubted anything, or anyone, could overtake the old warrior. He tried not to think about it, but this thought included him as well. <br>
<br>
He had found little information from the Fellowship as well. Though powerful and learned travelers each, their priorities seemed to rest more in the enjoyment of each other’s company, and the pursuit of personal goals that drew them together. Theirs was not a guild of knowledge. <br>
<br>
Brendyn decided to spend one more day in the alleys, pumping the vagabonds for information. With nothing else to go on, his prospects looked dim, but there was nowhere else to go. This was Tir na Nog, a small capital compared to his homeland, but a capital nonetheless. <br>
<br>
The day passed with little accomplished. As evening approached, Brendyn had given up. Turning to leave, he noticed a young boy studying him, though he tried his best not to appear to be doing that very thing. Knowing the trick all too well from the streets he grew up on, Brendyn began to leave, heading directly towards the boy. <br>
<br>
The bard flexed his hands, looking forward to blowing off some frustration by teaching this young thief a lesson. However, instead of moving toward his mark, the young buy turned down a nearby alley, giving Brendyn a slight glance as he did. Brendyn had utilized the services of street informants in the past, and knew this game as well. Slowing down his stride, he walked around the corner, keeping the boy, who was already half way down the alley, just in his sights. <br>
<br>
After following him around twists and turns for nearly half an hour, Brendyn finally came around a corner, to see the young boy standing before him. <br>
<br>
The boy was dirty. This fact was the first thing to strike any observer, and was a difficult thing to get past. Having dealt with all types of people from all walks of life, Brendyn continued to study him. His clothes were ripped, soiled from the garbage he probably slept in. His hair was uncut, tucked underneath a filthy cloth hat, one he probably either stole or found discarded. He wore a thick cloak, but upon closer examination, it was found to be a tablecloth, “found” at one of the many taverns within the city no doubt. The boy was young, and small in stature. Thin, but not famished, his slight build seemed weighed down by his clothes, but could just as easily be the mantle of poverty worn about his shoulders for countless months, if not years. <br>
<br>
“What do you have for me?” Brendyn said, hoping to get this business over with. <br>
<br>
“ere now, that not the ay it works, m’ord.”, the boy replied, a smirk slowing forming on his filthy face. <br>
<br>
“I beg to differ. You’ve spent my time, which is rather precious to me,” the bard replied, a matching smirk growing on his face. Brendyn pulled back his cloak, allowing the boy to glance at the bastard sword hanging easily from his belt. “I would not want to be the person to take that time, and waste it. Now, tell me what you know, or tell me that you’ve wasted my time,” Brendyn finished, the smirk replaced with a deadly serious stare. <br>
<br>
The street urchin stared at the blade, looking as if he was suddenly going to run for it. Brendyn, feeling more at home now then he had over the past few months, pulled back the other side of his cloak, revealing a very thick coin purse. All thought of leaving left the young boy, his eyes drawn to the sight of more money then he had ever seen. <br>
<br>
“My time is short, boy. Maybe you misunderstood me. I will pay you, and pay you well for your information, as long as it is useful to me. Now, tell me what you know,” Brendyn said. <br>
<br>
“Vencklayne,” said the boy. <br>
<br>
Had Brendyn not been tired from his previous fruitless searches, and so far away from home, he might have been able to hide his excitement, the first rule of negotiation. Had he been aware of his own expression, he would have chided himself days later. <br>
<br>
Instead, Brendyn could only stare, his dull, tired eyes replaced with a gleam. <br>
<br>
“Tell me more,” Brendyn said, a slight edge seeping into his voice. <br>
<br>
Brendyn left by horseback that very night, headed south to the location detailed by the young boy. He knew that he would only be wasting his time staying in Tir na Nog, being too excited to even sleep this night. Finally, a lead. Finally, he would have his chance. <br>
<br>
His chance for revenge. <br>
<br>
The young street boy opened the back door to his abode, tossing aside the gold coins he had received from the bard to the beggar sitting next to the alley. His anonymous “tip” for the services of a guard. The type that was never noticed, even by the rogue’s guild. Stepping inside, the young boy stripped out of his dirty street clothes, heading first to the bath. Removing the filthy cap from his head, his pointed ears poked out above his hair, slightly sore from being tucked down beneath the hat. Stretching to his full height, he still stood below six feet. Short and young, even compared to other elves, the rogue had perfected his disguise as a street urchin. The man cleaned up, replacing his rags with his well-oiled black leather armor. The rogue ran his fingers through his golden hair, cleaned and brushed after the recent bath. Already smiling from his latest accomplishment, he glanced over where his weapons rested, grabbing his large magical black cloak. His weapons shared a table with an old, threadbare tomb, nondescript and unmarked. The rogue had to laugh aloud, thinking of all that he had accomplished in the past few days. The book was safely his, ready to be delivered to his employer. The only person to know about it left for dead in the tomb of the Muire family. He smiled, thinking of the bonus he would receive for taking care of that nosy bard, the last person to know of Vencklayne. <br>
<br>
He glanced outside, noting the position of the moon. The bard would make it to the camp in an hour at most. The rogue grinned from ear to ear at that thought. <br>
<br>
Midnight couldn’t come soon enough.<br>
