<br>
Brendyn glanced over his shoulder, feeling the wind rush past his face. His gaze fell upon the rising moon, peaking above the trees of Tir na mBeo. Brendyn settled back into the saddle of his horse, deciding that he would make it in time. The street informant told him to make it to the camp by midnight, and judging by his directions, it would be a little ways into the forest nearby. <br>
<br>
The forest where Vencklayne lived. <br>
<br>
Brendyn rode past Ardagth, just another horse rider on the trail to the south to those who even noticed. Save one. A set of eyes marked his passage, with a little more than a passing interest. The owner of those eyes walked calmly over to the stable master, purchasing a horse to ride to Connla, hoping to follow the cloaked bard. <br>
<br>
Brendyn’s arrival in Connla was met with little attention, many of the inhabitants already gone to bed. Tethering his horse at the stable, he glanced around, found the right direction, and headed into the forest. Although he had time, he was not sure how long it would take to find the campsite, and did not want to miss his chance. <br>
<br>
The informant said that Vencklayne always visited the campsite at midnight, some sentimental reason that only an elf would hold, and only an elf would know. The reason was not important, however, it was the chance to catch the wily warrior out in the open that mattered to Brendyn. <br>
<br>
He arrived at the camp, noting that the moon still shone before its apex. Brendyn nodded, finding one of the empty tents to be suitable for his trap. Then, he laid in wait, flexing his hands and wiping the sweat from his eyes. <br>
<br>
Inside the tent, he could only see the immediately surrounding area. Had he been outside, he might have seen the slight glimmer of the moon coming from a nearby tree, shining off of a set of dull armor as the wearer breathed in the night sky. <br>
<br>
Brendyn felt it more than saw it. A presence, just outside the tent. Although he could not see anything from inside, he felt like he had pinpointed the location of the midnight visitor. A dark dread seized his heart then. Trusting his feelings, he quietly held up his sword, lining up his stab. With a yell, he leapt forward, through the tattered leather tent, directly diving for the heart of the presence. <br>
<br>
He tumbled to the side, suddenly very cold, his hand going numb. <br>
<br>
Untangling himself from the tent, Brendyn found himself sitting just outside the campsite. <br>
<br>
Staring right through a ghost. <br>
<br>
The specter turned to regard him, undamaged by his sudden attack. Brendyn looked down at his hand, surprised to see his sword lying on the ground next to him. His hand was so numb, he did not even feel the sword missing. <br>
<br>
The bard looked up, his face setting in the scream that his lungs would not make. One by one, more and more ghosts appeared at the campsite, each in succession turning to regard him, the intruder. <br>
<br>
A slight hiss, like ice hitting a red-hot coal, escaped the spirit’s mouth. Gathering around, and coming closer, Brendyn found himself in a situation he hadn’t been in for a long time. <br>
<br>
Brendyn didn’t know what to do. <br>
<br>
His feeling of helplessness and fear melted to sheer terror as the voice of the undead filled the night air. <br>
<br>
“ALBIONIAN!…INVADER!” <br>
<br>
Brendyn had been prepared for that call during his entire stay in Hibernia. From small village to large bustling city, from quiet meetings to loud taverns, Brendyn had been prepared to debunk any claim of his heritage, any accusation of his homeland. <br>
<br>
But there was no convincing the undead. Their proof was spiritual, able to sense that he did not belong here. He would not be able to talk his way out of this. Even as that realization sank in, he glanced at his sword lying on the ground next to him. Brendyn had his doubts about the effectiveness of fighting his way out as well. <br>
<br>
That left only one alternative, running. One he was particularly good at, or so he thought. Brendyn tried to rise to his feet, but found his body sapped of strength, the terror of the undead before him too much for his battered and weakened body. <br>
<br>
Brendyn smirked, preparing for the end. He found it a bit ironic that his end would come at the cause of his obsession for finding Vencklayne, although he had assumed it might, if only at the end of Vencklayne’s sword. <br>
<br>
Brendyn closed his eyes, as one of the spirits stopped before him, raising its sword to cut him asunder. His preparations for the afterlife were interrupted as a voice, a human voice, cried out. <br>
<br>
“BRENDYN!” <br>
<br>
A flash of steel, a flurry of cloak, and a sharp ringing of metal on metal assaulted his senses. Brendyn’s eyes snapped open, trying to figure out what just happened. <br>
<br>
Standing before him, staring down the ghosts with her sword drawn was a celtic heroine. Shaenon turned to glance at him. <br>
<br>
“Oh Brendyn, what have you done?” <br>
<br>
Brendyn could only stare back, shocked by her sudden appearance. His shock was quickly replaced with dread, as he saw the ghosts suddenly turn their attention to Shaenon. <br>
<br>
“Shaenon, you have to get out of here!” Brendyn cried, but was cut short by the look on Shaenon’s face as she regarded him. <br>
<br>
Peace. Calmness. Devotion. <br>
<br>
Love. <br>
<br>
Brendyn slowly closed his eyes, for the first time in his life, disgusted at what his charm spell was about to cost. For what his spell was about to do to this young, shy woman. <br>
<br>
He looked on in horror as Shaenon steeled her gaze onto the specters, raised her huge sword with one hand….and beckoned to the ghosts. <br>
<br>
Brendyn finally got his feet under him, and stood up, hoping that he would be able to offer something, anything, to the coming battle. The ghosts slowly stalked around Shaenon, their blades glowing softly in the moonlight. Shaenon and Brendyn stood their ground, awaiting the exchange of blows. <br>
<br>
The specters had a different idea. <br>
<br>
As one, they raised their free hands, each pointing a finger at Shaenon. Shaenon screamed out, her body suddenly covered in cuts by invisible blades. Brendyn prepared a spell of minor healing, hoping to at least stop the bleeding, to do something to stop this brave woman from dying before him. He found his voice trailing off as Shaenon turned her face to look at him. Her body was bleeding from numerous cuts, but Brendyn found himself unable to turn away from her face. <br>
<br>
The blue lines, celtic markings foreign to the bard, pulsed with a gleam barely seen in the darkness. Shaenon’s mouth slowly smiled at him, before contorting in a grimace. Brendyn stared on in fear, as Shaenon stared back, eyes suddenly a dark red. <br>
<br>
A vicious “pop” filled the air, and Shaenon let out a scream. Brendyn thought the noble heroine was under attack again, before the awful truth sunk in. Shaenon’s body began to contort, a growl escaping Shaenon’s lips. Suddenly rising to her feet, her body growing beyond the armor she wore, her hair growing tougher and tougher, becoming like hard bone. <br>
<br>
Transformed, the Celtic warrior towered over Brendyn, who stood transfixed by the sight. A forest spirit, easily holding the 2-handed sword with one hand, growled in defiance to the ghosts before her. <br>
<br>
The spirits seemed to take pause, perhaps a little surprised to see one so in tune with nature on the other side of the battlefield. As Brendyn studied their inactivity, he noticed for the first time that they were, or at least used to be, Elven. As Shaenon began her charge, the ghosts raised their hands again, this time not to cut down the raging Stag spirit, but to magically hold it in place. <br>
<br>
Brendyn’s heart sank as he saw Shaenon held tight by magical bonds, unable to get any closer to the spirits, her body weakened from the wounds she had suffered. A few moments later, she collapsed from exhaustion, her body reverting to its normal form. <br>
<br>
The ghosts, having dispatched the heroine, again turned their attention to Brendyn. Before they could even approach, Shaenon pulled herself up with her sword, gritting her teeth. <br>
<br>
“WAIT!” she cried out. <br>
<br>
The rest was lost to Brendyn, spoken in a language he did not know. It was not Elven, for he had overheard a few words in his travels, but somehow, the spirits understood it. They seemed appeased by whatever Shaenon had said, yet they did not move to leave, gathering instead in a semi-circle around Shaenon. <br>
<br>
The darkest horror Brendyn had ever felt suffocated him as what was happening began to sink in. It would have been appalling had Shaenon died during the battle for his sake, though he would probably not have had long to lament with his death quickly following. <br>
<br>
But this…this was agonizing. This was horrific. This wasn’t right. <br>
<br>
The ghosts waited, apparently agreeing to give Shaenon a few moments to finish any business she might have with the living; giving her a chance to say her goodbyes. <br>
<br>
To him, of all people. The person who caused her demise. <br>
<br>
Brendyn looked at his sword, lying next to him still. He stared, begging, pleading with his body to fight off the numbness and raise it up to save Shaenon’s life, even at the expense of his own. His own worthless, pathetic life. <br>
<br>
“Brendyn” Shaenon whispered, drawing him out of his internal battle, “stop. It’s over.” <br>
<br>
“No….NO!…there’s no reason for you to do this!…it isn’t right!” Brendyn sobbed. <br>
<br>
“Bren….let go of your guilt. This is my choice, my life. It is what I was charged to do.” <br>
<br>
The bard stared at her, the tears flowing from his eyes going unnoticed in this moment. <br>
<br>
“How can you say that?!…After what I did?!…You don’t deserve to die!” Brendyn cried. <br>
<br>
“You did nothing, young bard. I am a gypsy, knowing when I was very young that my life would be given, devoted even, to the protection of another. Your enchantments have no effect on me, but I knew there would be no other way to get you to allow me to keep my vow.” Shaenon whispered, her bleeding slowing as her life began to wane. <br>
<br>
Brendyn only stared, shocked. “Your vow?…to whom?” <br>
<br>
Shaenon smiled sadly, “I only wish I had the chance to be there, when you find the person you’re looking for. Though my life is not pointless, not in the least, your life is that much more important. You MUST survive, you must live on. Consider how important your role is, even now, if I am willing to give up my own so that you can succeed.” <br>
<br>
Shaenon coughed, feeling suddenly very light. Brendyn fell down to the grass beside her, forgetting about the twelve ghosts that surrounded them. <br>
<br>
Shaenon raised her hand to Brendyn’s face, caressing it softly. “You have to learn to trust them. Your road is a difficult one, one that you cannot do alone. My vow is kept, my life complete. Do not dishonor that by failing. Do not fail by being too proud to seek help. Be strong, Brendyn. I will be watching from beyond, and when the day comes that you pass over, I will hold you to telling me how you succeeded. Do not disappoint me,” she said, smiling as she closed her eyes for the last time. <br>
<br>
Brendyn did not notice that the ghosts had left. <br>
He did not notice as morning approached hours later. <br>
<br>
Later that day, Brendyn watched the sun set on the coast, resting on the cliff top that overlooked Connla. He looked down, to the place where Shaenon now laid, buried a few feet away. Haunted by her words, Brendyn tried to make sense out of what had happened to Shaenon, what she had meant, and why he was given another chance. <br>
<br>
Somehow he felt that Vencklayne would know.<br>
