<br>
The young man flinched as another line snapped free from the boat’s mast. This was the worst storm he had ever heard about, much less been in. He had grown up in a fishing town, near the coast, and boating had been a way of life ever since being old enough to swim. Another bolt of lightning struck the water near his vessel, demanding his focus on the job at hand. When the storm began, his first thought was returning home. Now, after nearly four hours of torrential rain, crashing waves, and dangerous lightning, his only thought was survival. Only an hour later, and his boat was capsized, his final thoughts were of his homeland. <br>
<br>
The young man awoke on a beach gently lapped by the waves. It had been ten years since his arrival here, and just recently, his dreams had been filled with that fateful day, brought on by his upcoming departure from this land, back into the sea. He thought back to his first meeting with his elven provider, just a young man himself. Both were surprised to see another living being out here. Both were fascinated by the others way of life. <br>
<br>
After six months, they learned enough of each other’s language to communicate every day with basic words. They built a hut to live in, and hunted for food nearby, the elven companion teaching the young man how to hunt the beasts of the forest. The human returned the favor, teaching the elf how his people earned their living on the sea, setting up water cages and fishing off shore. <br>
<br>
After one year, the elf had learned enough of the young man’s language to understand him fully. To understand the civil war ongoing back in his homeland. <br>
<br>
To find himself fascinated by tales of far away lands. <br>
<br>
After three years, the young man had learned enough of the elven language to understand it fluently, though he could still barely complete sentences with it. The elf spent the next year telling the young man about his own homeland, beyond the veil, and his interests in the outside world that drew him out. To him, the gathering of knowledge was the greatest goal of his life. <br>
<br>
They spent the next years trading information with each other: the young man taught as much as he knew about the outside world, their culture and livelihood, and the ways of the ocean and boating. The elf taught the young man the ways of the land: how to hunt, how to track and travel quietly through a forest. <br>
<br>
And how to fight with a blade. <br>
<br>
And now, ten years later, the young man was about to return home. The two had spent the last few years crafting a boat sturdy enough to allow him to return to his homeland. He was now 28, both were actually, though only in human years. The elven lad, still appearing quite young for 28, would live long beyond the life-span of the young man he had come to know so well. However, the years spent together had forged a friendship neither was prepared to give up. <br>
<br>
The young man sat up, glancing over at his newly crafted boat. All seemed in order, his preparations made to set out tomorrow morning. He looked back towards the hut that he and the elf had called home for the past ten years. <br>
<br>
He thought again of how much he would miss this place…. <br>
________________________________________________________________________ <br>
<br>
The elf looked out from the doorway to the hut he now called home, to the strange young man sitting down by the beach. So much had happened in that span of ten years, so much had been learned from this one young man. The elf’s thirst for knowledge was enough to drive him beyond the veil at such a young age, to return to the land populated by celts and firbolgs. And then, beyond his wildest dreams, a stranger from a distant, foreign land practically stumbled across his path. <br>
<br>
It had been a wonderful, informative ten years. The elf was not about to let it stop now. <br>
<br>
The elf glanced down at an orb, resting on the table next to a few souvenirs for the young man to take with him. The orb was small, only two inches in diameter. Its color matched the azure blue of the sky after a rainstorm, still glowing slightly from the enchantments placed on it. The elf would be working off that debt for some time to come, but the price was nothing compared to the power he now had in his grasp. <br>
<br>
The elf took a small parchment out, writing a few words with delicate strokes of a quill. He quickly rolled up the note, and touched the orb lying on the table. Without a sound or delay, the orb opened in half, revealing a compartment. The elf placed the note inside, closed the orb shut, and wrapped it in a few rags, placing it amongst the young mans items. Yes, ten years was a long time to gather information. <br>
<br>
But not nearly long enough for an elf.<br>
