<br>
Ereck woke early, eager to return to his patrol. It had been ten years since his return to his village, and his hometown had accomplished much. The civil war had ended, though bandits and rogues still roamed the outskirts of the larger cities, feeding off of the little hamlets like Ereck’s fishing village. Though individually they posed no threat to Ereck and the men of the village that he had trained in the basics of fighting, Ereck had always worried that they would only grow stronger and bolder as winter approached. <br>
<br>
Time had passed, and Ereck found himself aching more and more with each morning. His youth spent protecting the land he loved left him with many bruises and cuts, and himself feeling much older than he actually was. Ereck had taken a beautiful wife, a childhood friend more than happy to see him return so long ago. They gave birth to a son, whose fifth birthday was fast approaching. <br>
<br>
Ereck thought back fondly to the time he had spent in the elven land, idly picking up the strange blue orb his elven friend had given him. He thought, and not for the first time, how his own son might follow his footsteps, learn the elven arts of the forest, and protect the land Ereck had come to love. He turned the orb over in his hands, trying to remember the path his boat had taken between his land, and the elves. <br>
<br>
Ereck sighed, whispering to himself the impossibility of reaching him. <br>
<br>
With the name of the elf uttered, the globe slowly glowed, and opened., revealing a parchment rolled up and held within. <br>
<br>
Ereck read the note, surprise slowly replaced by excitement. With a smile upon his face, Ereck scribbled a note in reply, placed it within the orb, and closed it shut once more. Uttering the elven word for “return”, the orb’s glow increased in brightness, only to begin to fade. As the orb grew dark, Ereck held his breath as the orb itself disappeared. <br>
<br>
He could only hope that it would return properly to its master. <br>
_______________________________________________________________________ <br>
<br>
The elf looked up from his writing, watching with delight as the orb slowly came into focus. He had wondered just how long it would take for Ereck to figure out his little “gift”. Although he would not admit it to the human, he was impressed with how quickly the reply had come. Ten years was not a long time for an elf to wait. <br>
<br>
His slender elven hand grasping the orb, the elf uttered the word of opening. He read the note eagerly, only to find himself rather perplexed. He read it a second time, and a third, allowing the proposition to sink in. Perhaps he could still use this to his advantage. Although it was not part of the original agreement outlined within the note, the elf was sure it would not take much convincing to get Ereck to see things his way. <br>
<br>
Gathering information would be easy enough as he patrolled the areas around his village. Perhaps he would have to travel a bit farther than he might want, but with his child “safely” under the care of the elf, Ereck would surely try to appease his old master. <br>
<br>
The elven master gathered his equipment, and prepared for the journey ahead. He wrote a reply to Ereck, detailing the directions to the designated island. He included a small sketch of a map, knowing that one as skilled as Ereck would have no trouble finding the place in the open seas. <br>
<br>
The elf sent the orb back on its magical journey, and set out for the island. Although Ereck would have no trouble finding it, this would only be the master’s fifth trip on the ocean. He decided it might be best to get a head start on “young” Ereck.<br>
