<br>
The boy grinned, assured that his blade would finally hit its mark. This time, he would strike the master! <br>
<br>
The boy sat on the ground, trying to figure out what had just happened over the past three seconds: how he had been disarmed, and dropped with but a flick of the master’s wrist. <br>
<br>
The master chuckled, trying not to laugh too loud. Although the boy might think otherwise, the master knew that this one was probably his best student yet. <br>
<br>
The master had seen many generations of students pass through his doors since the day Ereck had reached out to him for help. He approached each new challenge with youthful zest, finding each new student to be brighter and faster than the last. This one in particular had mastered the basics of sword combat in but two years. <br>
<br>
At the age of fourteen. <br>
<br>
The master generally left sword fighting as the last stage of training, allowing his students to grow into their new muscles, but the joy his latest student had shown in his studies of warfare simply overpowered the elf’s original plan. This one would be a wise tactician, and a fierce warrior. Exactly what his homeland now needed. <br>
<br>
The master dismissed his student to his daily chores, retiring to his chambers. The elf was saddened by the latest information reports coming in from his student’s father. The 40-year war had reached a crescendo of activity, with many battles ending in the death of those who dared to defend their land from the bandit army. The master sighed, and returned to the work at hand. <br>
<br>
He sat at his desk, opening the book resting there. Printed neatly across its cover were the words &quot;Beyond the veil, an anthology of the known information about the lands outside our home.&quot; <br>
<br>
Turning to the next empty page, the master began to scribe the latest information he had collected. <br>
________________________________________________________________________ <br>
<br>
The master stretched as he waited at the shore of the island meeting place. He was surprised to hear so quickly this time from his previous student, Umael, who was already wishing for his master to take on his next student. As Umael’s boat approached, the master wondered how much he would be able to accomplish, feeling the age that had seeped into his bones and muscles. <br>
<br>
Umael approached, followed by a young woman. This was certainly a first. Not surprisingly, his students had always been men. Perhaps it was just luck of the draw, the first born always being a man. Perhaps his students did not want to submit their daughters to such trials. The master did not waste much time on it personally. <br>
<br>
The master waited to hear exactly what Umael, his brightest student in the ways of knowledge, had in mind. <br>
<br>
“Master, I fear to inconvenience you, but our needs have changed.” <br>
<br>
“Oh?” the master asked, already knowing the answer but still curious of where Umael was going with this conversation. <br>
<br>
“Yes master. Our lands have finally come to love peace, the war ending shortly before I had returned home. Although I have tried in earnest to secure that peace, there are many that hunger for political power.” <br>
<br>
The master nodded, his own studies in politics telling him as much, and already formulating a plan. <br>
<br>
“I’ve come to the decision that our child should be raised to be a leader of men. I would be forever grateful if you could teach our daughter your knowledge of men, and of politics. Surely you have collected a vast amount of information in such things. Just the formative years, for she needs to return to our homeland at an early enough age to enter into the political world to work her way into a position of leadership. I fear I returned to old to work my way into the system.” <br>
<br>
“Formative years? Early age? Your daughter seems to be quite old enough already,” the master said, his older age loosing his tactful speech. <br>
<br>
Umael smiled, as did the woman behind him. “No master, this is my wife. Our daughter is still quite young.” <br>
<br>
Umael’s wife unwrapped the bundle she held close to her body, exposing their young daughter for the first time since leaving their homeland. <br>
<br>
The master shook his head, “I am not a child raiser, student Umael. This is not satisfactory at all!” <br>
<br>
“Master, I know I am asking much. But I feel this is very important, and therefore am willing to make…sacrifices.” <br>
<br>
“Oh?” asked the master, his curiosity entering his voice. <br>
<br>
“Our sailors have found the location of two other countries, untapped resources for your book”, Umael smiled, having taken a peek through the book his master had been writing. Just as Umael had expected, a new life seemed to shine out of the master’s eyes. <br>
<br>
“Well then, let us begin at once. Tell me, who might my newest student be?” asked the master. <br>
<br>
Umael smiled, as he always did when speaking about his daughter. <br>
<br>
“Her name is Tyl. Tyl Villenria”<br>
