<br>
Kaejar was afraid. He wouldn’t admit it to his companions, would barely admit it to himself. But it was there. Fear. This was the lurikeen’s first trip into the tombs of the Muire family, the tombs that he had heard about since he was just a boy. Stupid dares! Why did he say yes? <br>
<br>
Pride. No other reason. With Nydira watching on, there was no chance he could say no. He had to impress her, and this was his first and only chance. Being the youngest of the kids that lived in Ardee, he would have been teased and belittled for the rest of his life had he said no. <br>
<br>
So here he was, an aspiring adventurer, with his most trusted friends. The four of them, on a search for the Hell Hag of Muire Tomb. Legend claimed that she could be seen wandering the halls of the deserted tomb, and only the bravest had escaped with their lives, much less defeated her. Kaejar swallowed hard, second-guessing the wisdom in hunting such a feared creature, and getting his best friends involved with it as well. <br>
<br>
“Look!” whispered Crauf, Kaejar’s best friend. “There she is!” <br>
<br>
Kaejar’s eyes grew big, as he looked down the dark hall, seeing a form stalk slowly toward them. Its hair was matted with sludge, cobwebs surrounded its body, grasping with the grip of the dead to the form’s clothes, dirty beyond recognition. Kaejar held his breath, his rugged bow shaking in his hands. <br>
<br>
“What are you doing Kaejar?” whispered Crauf. “Shoot her, quick!” <br>
<br>
Kaejar reached for an arrow, fumbling a few to the floor around him. Drawing back as far as he dared, he steadied his gaze, and let fly the arrow. <br>
<br>
The hag dropped to the floor with a thud. <br>
<br>
Kaejar and his friends grinned, congratulating Kaejar with slaps on the back. He would be the hero of Ardee! He would prove his worth to the beautiful Nydira! <br>
<br>
Crauf was the first to see the hag move. <br>
<br>
Silenced by the growl from across the hall, Kaejar looked up to see the hag slowly rise to its feet. <br>
<br>
Crauf was the first to reach the stairs, followed quickly by Kaejar’s other friends. <br>
<br>
Kaejar stared at the hag, his hands gripping his bow, his feet frozen in place. He could not pull his eyes from the horrible monster as it stalked slowly towards him. As it lumbered into the light, Kaejar’s eyes went wide. <br>
<br>
A woman! A warrior! What had he done?! Kaejar stared, seeing the woman covered in slime, blood, and webs. <br>
<br>
The woman looked down at the young lurikeen, and then glanced to the bow still held in his hands. She smiled slightly, trying to ignore the pain in her leg. <br>
<br>
“I think you dropped this,” Tyl said, handing the boy the arrow she had deftly evaded moments ago. Turning to pass, Tyl approached the stairs. <br>
<br>
“Wait!” Kaejar said. “You mean you’re not the Hell Hag?” <br>
<br>
Tyl looked back at the young boy, a slow smile showing on her face. She tossed a few strands of cloth at the boy’s feet. “Sorry, she didn’t think it was time for me to leave. I had to convince her.” <br>
<br>
As the blademaiden left, Kaejar looked down at the mummified cloth lying before him. <br>
<br>
A slow smile grew on his face. Boy would they be surprised when he returned! <br>
<br>
________________________________________________________________________ <br>
<br>
Laroac grinned at his assistant, counting the day’s take happily at a nearby desk. Today had been a good day, with many people visiting the city. It was with a bit of reluctance that he accepted the unexpected visitor. <br>
<br>
“Yes, what is it?” Laroac asked, always in a sour mood when interrupted from counting money. <br>
<br>
The short elf just smirked, wrapped in his black cloak, quietly standing before the rogue boss. <br>
<br>
Laroac shifted uncomfortably in his seat, unsure how to proceed. His ire only increased when he noticed the elf silently chuckling to himself! Before he could say a word, the elf cut him off. <br>
<br>
“You’ve already forgotten about me? Fine enough.” the elf said, pulling a book out from under his cloak. “Here’s the book you requested. Pay me my money, and I will be on my way.” <br>
<br>
Laroac couldn’t help but smile when the smirk disappeared off the elf’s face as his reward was thrown upon the floor in front of him. No one would speak to him in such a matter! He had a reputation to uphold! That would put this arrogant elf in his place. <br>
<br>
The elf stared holes into the rogue boss, refusing to bend down to retrieve the purse of coins lying before him. Laroac only laughed in his face, his personal guard moving a bit closer as his attendant walked up and took the book from the hands of the elf <br>
<br>
Laroac quieted, when the elf finally smirked. Without a word, he turned, walking calmly out of the room. The purse of coins laid untouched, on the floor where the elf had stood. As the door closed behind the young elf, Laroac’s guards broke into laughter, joined shortly thereafter by the assistant as he picked up the money purse, and placed it back on the table. <br>
<br>
Laroac chuckled, trying to forget about what just transpired. He was just one elf, Laroac told himself. <br>
<br>
What could one elf possibly do? <br>
<br>
________________________________________________________________________ <br>
<br>
The hall was rather quiet. Although a few of the guild had gathered to share stories and drink, the patrons kept the volume rather low. <br>
<br>
Sylaria, Easyn, and Thiule gathered around a table, listening to the young nightshade Evelynne’s latest stories of battle against invaders. Nokekula and Starrag stood near the bar, debating tactics for the coming raid. Near the fireplace, Gilrondaar sat taking a much-needed rest, rubbing the ears of faithful Darkpaws, curled up before his feet. <br>
<br>
All eyes turned to the door, every voice going quiet, when the blue-cloaked bard slowly walked in. <br>
<br>
In his hands was a large shield bearing the emblem of the Fellowship of Dihn. Strapped to his back was a huge two-handed sword. Its name was Destruction; know by appearance to a few of the guild as the sword Shaenon had used. <br>
<br>
Brendyn walked over to the wall, where many weapons had been hung, retired for good or for just a break by the patrons of the tavern. The bard removed the blade from his back, and placed it upon the wall, hanging the shield next to it. Brendyn’s hand lingered near the blade for a moment, as all in the tavern watched the scene before them. <br>
<br>
Brendyn turned, and met the gaze of each guild mate in turn. Brendyn removed his light blue cloak, hanging it underneath the memorial to Shaenon. Nodding to the witnesses before him, he pulled a cloak from his pack, and fastened it around his shoulders as he left. <br>
<br>
