<br>
The young man stood in the shade of the building, comfortably cool during the hot afternoon. Returning to Ardee was always a bittersweet visit for him. Growing up as one of the shorter elves ever seen, he was constantly the runt of the group. He took it all in stride, trying not to show just how much it hurt. Just how much he wanted to belong. <br>
<br>
He shook those thoughts from his mind, reminding himself that he had business to attend to. The elf waited patiently, knowing that Kaejar had never been late before. Even though he was a young boy, the lurikeen had shown a surprising maturity for his age. The youngest of the current group of children growing up in Ardee, Kaejar found himself in much the same position that the elf had: Always the one to be teased. Perhaps that was what had drawn the elven rogue’s attention to him, though the elf always told himself it was because no one suspected the boy would be working for a thief from Tir na Nog. <br>
<br>
The elf could not refuse to notice his jealous feelings when he saw Kaejar this morning, apparently the new “leader” of the youngsters of Ardee. <br>
<br>
Kaejar left the group, walking over to join the elf, knowing even as he did not see him that the elf would be standing there, in the shadows. A contented smile was on his face as he greeted the rogue. <br>
<br>
“What do you have for me today, lurikeen?” the elf spit out, a little more ire slipping into his voice and words then he meant to show. <br>
<br>
Kaejar’s face went dark, as he turned and looked away. The rogue was quick to respond. “Forgive me Kaejar, I have much on my mind this day. So who are the new warriors passing through Ardee this week?” <br>
<br>
The lurikeen’s face went blank, as he looked up at the elf. Clearing his throat, he said “You…you promise not to tell anyone about this?” <br>
<br>
The rogue could not hide his surprise. “My dear little friend, who was it that brought you the wondrous gem for your girlfriend Nydira? Of course you can trust me. I’d thought us better friends that that.” <br>
<br>
Kaejar smiled, remembering the look on his dear Nydira’s face when he gave her the gem. “Well, while hunting the Hell Hag in Muire tomb, I came across an amazing woman. She single-handedly fought her way up from the tomb, dispatching the Hell Hag herself. She…she gave me the hag’s scraps, so that I might claim her as my own kill” he finished, looking a little sheepish. <br>
<br>
The elf had to smile at this, aware of Kaejar’s new notoriety amongst the youngsters of Ardee. The smile only grew wider as the lurikeen continued. <br>
<br>
“She was a blademaster, dressed in blue armor, with fiery red spiked hair.” <br>
<br>
The elf was already pondering this new development as he said, “Please, dear little Kaejar, tell me more of this blademaster…everything that you remember.” <br>
<br>
Kaejar’s eyes lit up as the elf punctuated his request with a large, red ruby. <br>
<br>
______________________________________________________________ <br>
<br>
Tyl walked into Tir na Nog, no worse for the wear from her adventure in the tomb of Muire. Her clothes were washed, and her wounds clean. To any guardian she passed on the streets leading in to the capital, she appeared like any other warrior returning to the town after an extended trip away. <br>
<br>
Tyl’s real wounds were much deeper, beyond the view of casual observers. <br>
<br>
Her heart was heavy with failure. The last strong lead to the answers she sought was long cold, lost to the shadows. She considered the watchers, but doubted they would welcome her back. No, she decided, she was on her own. The book was the key, she was certain. Perhaps she could find out who was after it. These thoughts consumed her mind as she walked into her home in Tir na Nog. Closing the door, Tyl tried to think of where to start her search. Thinking another reading of the letter may yield some more clues, she turned to head upstairs. <br>
<br>
Her eyes were drawn back to a corner across the room. Even though she had not been home in a very long time, Tyl instinctually noticed the shadow thrown by the table; it’s length just a little too long. Before she could draw her blades, she recognized the laugh coming from behind the table. <br>
<br>
A young elven woman rose from the shadow, a smile on her face. <br>
<br>
“I almost had you, Lady Tyl!” laughed the elf, shaking her head. <br>
<br>
“Indeed you did, Lady Evelynne! I will have to keep my eyes out for you, as I see you have grown quite a bit since last I saw you. To think the same girl who brashly tried to walk in unnoticed just months before stands hidden before me now!” Tyl finished, a sincere grin on her face. <br>
<br>
A thought suddenly occurred to Tyl. Perhaps the young Evelynne could help Tyl out more than merely distracting her from her dark thoughts. <br>
<br>
“Evelynne, do you have contacts within any of the rogue’s guilds within the city?” Tyl said. <br>
<br>
“Not many, but I’ve a few friends. What might you be looking for?” <br>
<br>
“A man. An elf, though short for your race. Dressed in a rich black cloak, with golden hair. He had just completed a job for someone involving a book taken from Muire tomb.” <br>
<br>
“Well milady Tyl, I would be happy to see what-“ <br>
<br>
Evelynne stopped suddenly, her eyes staring behind Tyl to a corner. Tyl spun around, her own eyes going wide with shock. She heard Evelynne draw her blades, preparing to leap ahead and attack the intruder, but all Tyl could do was stare at the man. <br>
<br>
The man simply smiled at Evelynne, his arms folded across his chest, his dark black cloak wrapped around his body, no weapons in sight. <br>
<br>
“I suggest you hold your place, little girl. This doesn’t concern you. Or would you strike down the man offering the information your friend Tyl seeks?”<br>
