<br>
Tyl stared long and hard at the building across from the alley that she found herself in. A simple three-story structure, like many of the homes in Tir na Nog. Upon closer inspection, she did notice a young man that seemed to be standing rather close to the door most of the time.<br>
<br>
Tyl turned around to the rogue sharing the alley with her, to ask him about this man, this “rogue guild”.<br>
<br>
She found him dipping a dart into a small vial.<br>
<br>
“What are you doing?!” she hissed, trying not to be too loud.<br>
<br>
The elf looked up from his careful work, only briefly.<br>
<br>
“I’m trying to get just enough of this sleep poison so that I don’t kill the young man guarding the door,” he said. With a disinterested look, he returned to his work.<br>
<br>
Tyl reached out a hand, grabbing his arm to get his attention. “I don’t think we need to-“<br>
<br>
The rest of her words were lost in the intense cold stare that the elf returned to her. Tyl fell back a step, trying to discern if this man was about to attack her. Was he actually shaking?<br>
<br>
The rogue visibly calmed, taking a steadying breath. But the look in his eyes remained.<br>
<br>
“Do not touch me.”<br>
<br>
His gaze held on Tyl for a moment longer, and then he returned to his work. Tyl could only blink in response.<br>
<br>
The elf finished his work, and looked up to the doorway. Without turning around he said, “Stay here. When you see the guard walk away from the door, count to five. If he doesn’t turn around, make your run then. The door will be unlocked. Open the door, rush in, and engage the four guards on the first floor. I will be right behind you.”<br>
<br>
Tyl stared at the rogue, expecting him to turn around and give her that annoying smirk.<br>
<br>
Instead, he merely stood up and padded off toward another side alley.<br>
<br>
<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Tyl watched as the guard walked off, counted to five, and headed for the door. Sure enough, the door was unlocked. She opened the door, ran inside, and looked for the guards.<br>
<br>
Her gaze was met by six very surprised thieves.<br>
<br>
Tyl noticed two things instantly. One, there were six guards, not four. This in itself was rather disturbing. The second thing she noticed was that none of their gazes were shifting behind her:<br>
<br>
To where the rogue, her “backup”, was supposed to be entering from.<br>
<br>
Tyl sighed, looking behind her just to make sure. She returned her gaze to the thieves before her, as they each reached for their weapons.<br>
<br>
Tyl shrugged, drawing her own blades.<br>
<br>
“Well then, guess we might as well start this dance. And me with no date. Any takers for first dance?”<br>
<br>
<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Tyl ran up the stairs to the third floor, cursing the rogue who led her into this disaster. But there was no chance to turn around now. The book was upstairs, and she wasn’t about to pass up on this, her only lead.<br>
<br>
She rounded the stairs landing, coming to a stop. A long hallway stretched out before her, longer than the building itself. It obviously tunneled into the mountain behind the house. Down the hall ahead of her laid the bodies of ten rogues. Before she could even fathom what happened, she heard noises from below. Reinforcements.<br>
<br>
Then she heard a sound that sent a shiver down her spine: the barking of dogs. Guild houses were notorious for raising the meanest dogs ever seen, almost like wolves. Intimidated, beaten, mistreated, they were bred for the sole purpose of tearing apart an intruder.<br>
<br>
Tyl ran down the hall, trying each door, but all were locked. Half way down the hall, she heard the dogs on the stairs behind her. Turning around, she stood her ground, blades drawn.<br>
<br>
Three dogs rounded the bend, their eyes latching on to Tyl, their mouths drooling. As they rushed forward, Tyl steeled her gaze.<br>
<br>
Suddenly, she heard a voice cry out, in a language she did not understand. But the voice carried weight, the word sounding like a command. Immediately, the dogs stopped their charge. Two of the dogs curled up on the floor, and went to sleep. The third loped back to the stairs, where a celt in dark robes immerged.<br>
<br>
The dog yapped happily as the man stroked its muzzle, petting the dog on the head as he turned to face Tyl. A sincere grin came across his face.<br>
<br>
“Tyl! Guess I stopped by in time.”<br>
<br>
Tyl could only smile at the mentalist standing before her.<br>
<br>
“Well, I guess you did Easyn. Thanks for coming, even though I forgot your invitation.”<br>
<br>
Easyn smiled in return, his face suddenly going serious. “Tyl, behind you!”<br>
<br>
Tyl turned to see a man with a short bow standing in front of the door at the end of the hall. An evil grin on his face as his arrow was aimed at Tyl’s heart.<br>
<br>
The sound of a whizzing arrow passed by Tyl’s ear in a flash of blue. It took her a moment to realize that it passed from behind her, toward the bowman.<br>
<br>
The bowman stood surprised, trying to figure out what just happened. An arrow, his arrow, fell to his feet. His hands started to shake as he looked to his bow, to see that the string was cleanly cut, a stilleto perched perfectly where it once was.<br>
<br>
Everyone in the hall focused their gaze at the young elven ranger calmly rise from her roll and lunge before the archer, her weapons already being replaced.<br>
<br>
The ranger turned around to see what everyone was staring at. Suddenly, she giggled, and returned their stares, throwing a wink Tyl and Easyn’s way, and a suddenly calm, determined glance to the terrified bowman.<br>
<br>
“Oh come on now, don’t look like that. Don’t you have any more arrows in that quiver? Looks like…five, six more? Listen, I’ll give you another chance,&quot; she stated, and started to walk back down to the other side of the hall.  &quot;Surely you’ve got another string in there. Go ahead, restring that bow. Come on, come on, we haven’t got all day….”<br>
<br>
The ranger giggled again as the bowman threw his bow down, running past the three and down the stairs.<br>
<br>
“Can never find a taker for that bet,” she said, shaking her head.<br>
<br>
Easyn and Tyl each smiled at the ranger, having witnessed her speed many times before.<br>
<br>
“Perhaps everyone you’ve run into is still sane, friend Sylaria?” Easyn chided.<br>
<br>
Sylaria paused to ponder this statement, for only a moment before a grin took in her face. “I guess I’ll just have to keep looking,” she said, a playful dejection seeping into her voice.<br>
<br>
“But Tyl, what are you doing here?” Easyn said, their friendly banter replaced by the need at hand.<br>
<br>
“There’s something I need to retrieve here, as well as a certain rogue to repay for his treachery,” Tyl said, turning to look at the last door at the end of the hall.<br>
<br>
Sylaria and Easyn exchanged glances, a plan formulated in mere moments.<br>
<br>
Easyn began a chant, calming Tyl’s mind from exhaustion and mending her wounds. Sylaria voiced her support, saying, “We’ll take care of the reinforcements below, you just do what you need to do friend.”<br>
<br>
Tyl nodded in thanks, and headed for the end of the hall without turning around. She knew she could trust her friends.<br>
<br>
As Tyl approached, she heard voices coming from the last room. Loud voices:<br>
<br>
“You have no idea how much money that is worth! I’ll…I’ll give you half…all! I’ll give you it all, just don’t kill me!” a voice cried out, full of terror.<br>
<br>
“You don’t get it, do you!? Even now…especially now, you continue to insult me?! You think this is about the MONEY?!” a second voice, rising in power, consumed by rage.<br>
<br>
“What do you want?!” the first voice, now desperate, cried.<br>
<br>
Tyl could only hear the second voice, suddenly deathly calm, but could not make out the words. A moment later, one of the voices screamed in horror, then suddenly went quiet.<br>
<br>
Tyl threw open the door, to find a man lying face down on the floor. Standing just beyond him, perched on a windowsill, was the elven rogue, wrapped in his black cloak.<br>
<br>
Under his arm was the threadbare book.<br>
<br>
Even now, after expecting every word spoken by the rogue to be a lie, Tyl was crushed by this last betrayal. Suddenly unable to take it anymore, with exhaustion seeping in, and Easyn’s calming spell wearing off, Tyl broke down, falling to her knees on the floor.<br>
<br>
The rogue sat there for a long moment, looks of regret and pain crossing his face very briefly as he watched the tears fall from Tyl’s eyes.<br>
<br>
“I’m….I’m sorry.”<br>
<br>
Tyl looked up, choking back the sobs.<br>
<br>
The rogue shook his head, the blank stare replaced.<br>
<br>
“I’m sorry………..but this book must be destroyed.”<br>
<br>
Unable to look Tyl in the eye any longer, the rogue dropped out of the window to the street below.<br>
<br>
