<br>
The elven rogue smiled briefly as he watched Tyl enter into the rogue guild house. Having heard the tale of Tyl’s escape from Muire tomb, he had no concerns about her ability to fight any inside of the rogue guild. Nodding to himself, he turned to find his own entrance. <br>
<br>
He chuckled to himself as he rounded to the back of the guild house. They thought they were so smart, hiding the window above the marketplace, impossible to see from any angle in the street below. He savored chances like this, the perfect finale to the events he had already set in motion for the guild house. He had patiently waited for the perfect time to exploit that weakness, putting petty insults and cheap opportunity aside, reminding himself to save this knowledge for just the perfect time. <br>
<br>
That time was today. <br>
<br>
Climbing the side of the mountain did not pose much of a challenge for the nimble elf, and he was quickly beside the windowsill of the guild masters office. <br>
<br>
He peaked in, listening with keen elven ears to the conversation going on. It seemed that the defenses were in disarray, unprepared for a warrior such as Tyl to enter the premises unannounced. However, steps were being taken to fend off the intrusion. The elven rogue heard the master order out his remaining guards, trusting that the only entrance to be gained would come from that hallway. <br>
<br>
The elf smiled. <br>
_______________________________________________________________ <br>
<br>
Laroac watched the last of his guards leave, shuffling over to his personal weapons cabinet. He looked through his collection, trying to find something that he may be able to use, just in case. <br>
<br>
“Come now, you don’t REALLY think that’s going to make a difference, do you?” <br>
<br>
The voice stopped him cold. Laroac turned around to find the black-clad elven rogue perched on his windowsill. <br>
<br>
“How…how…how did you get in here?” <br>
<br>
The elf smirked, glancing at the windowsill he was sitting on. “Probably through this window.” <br>
<br>
The guild master stammered a few more times, suddenly realizing who was now staring at him, and not too kindly. He fell back as the rogue hopped off the sill, in stunned silence as the elf quickly surveyed the room’s contents. <br>
<br>
“What, just a common thief, trying to come in here and steal from me? I’ll have you know that I’ve an army of guards just past that door. One word from me-” <br>
<br>
The elf laughed, not even looking over at the man. <br>
<br>
“At first, I just thought you were ignorant, perhaps just rude. Now, I truly see that you are an idiot,” the elf finished, picking up a threadbare book off of the desk. <br>
<br>
“Wait, what are you doing? You can’t take that!” <br>
<br>
The elf finally turned to regard the man, a smirk on his face. “I’m sorry, did you say I CAN’T take this? You hardly look like a man in a position to make demands.” <br>
<br>
The elf’s smirk disappeared as the man began to laugh at him, replaced with a blank stare before finally settling on a slow boiling anger. <br>
<br>
“You have no idea what that is, do you? That book you hold contains information very valuable, to some very powerful people. Stealing that will only mark you as an enemy, and your life will quickly come to an end,” said the guild master. As if drawing strength from his own words, he stood up to the short elf. <br>
<br>
The elf took a quick glance through the book while the man talked, soaking in the gist of the contents. Snapping the book shut, he interrupted the guild masters taunts. <br>
<br>
“Do you really think you could sell this to those people? You really ARE stupid. What’s to stop them from just killing you outright…” the elf stopped, suddenly seeing the game for what it was. <br>
<br>
“You have no intention of selling this to Fagan’s men, do you?” the elf accused, seeing immediately that his words had hit the mark, as the guild master shrunk back to the floor. <br>
<br>
“You’d actually sell out your homeland for some money?! You’re thinking to make a deal with Albion or Midgard? Where do you think you’ll go with this money? I should kill you now as a traitor” <br>
<br>
“What does it matter to me? I’m not a young man; my time will pass before this land sees any change because of it. This might even save Hibernia, with the information in that book, they could wage a much more profitable war against either of the other countries,” the guild master mused. <br>
<br>
The elf’s face turned serious, his blades finding his hands in an instant. For a moment, he thought of the poor he saw in Tir na Nog everyday, of those unfortunate people who had nothing to look forward to but living another day under the sun of Hibernia. <br>
<br>
He thought of Kaejar and Nydira, the future of his homeland. <br>
<br>
“You would discard the futures of those who call Hibernia home, for some cheap gold?” the elf spit, indignant. <br>
<br>
“Some cheap gold? You have no idea how much money that is worth! I’ll…I’ll give you half…all! I’ll give you it all, just don’t kill me!” the guild master pleaded. <br>
<br>
The elven rogue lost all composure, infuriated by this man who would so easily consider him as nothing more than trash, first by disregarding him, and now by thinking he could so easily be bought. <br>
<br>
“You don’t get it, do you!? Even now…especially now, you continue to insult me?! You think this is about the MONEY?!” the elf shouted, overcome with rage. <br>
<br>
“What do you want?!” the guild master cried. <br>
<br>
The elf calmed visibly, a slow smirk overcoming his face. <br>
<br>
“I want you to listen to every word I am going to say. Right now, as we speak, your guild house is in shambles. A lone warrior has conquered your men. That same warrior was within my grasp, to provide to you. With that simple knowledge, all of this would have been averted. However, you had to mock me, to belittle me. Because of that simple action, she was able to overcome your meager defenses, and ruin you today. And trust me when I say you are ruined. What rogue would join a guild that cannot even defend against one lone woman? But if it merely stopped there, you might be able to repair your reputation, and recover the losses you suffered this day. And yet, I must continue. I feel obligated to report you to Fagan’s men, anonymously of course, although I’m sure it won’t take long for them to check my story out. Honestly, offering information to our enemies? That’s treason. You’ll be hung by sundown. <br>
<br>
“Except I know you and your type too well. You won’t take your death like a man, you’ll run, and run far. You’ll try and gather as many men, and as much gold as you can, and make a life for yourself somewhere else. But then what would your lesson be? No, I can’t allow that,” the elf said, that evil smirk on his face from ear to ear. <br>
<br>
“Instead, as soon as I finish this sentence, I will poison you with this sleep poison, and you will awake to find yourself with mere minutes to make your escape,” the elf said, poking the man with a small needle. <br>
<br>
“Welcome to the working class, fool!” the elf snickered, laughing directly in the man’s face as he fought the poison. <br>
<br>
The guild master screamed, trying to work his way to the door to call to his guards, but instead he slumped to the ground, fast asleep. <br>
<br>
The elf turned to leave, arriving on the windowsill, when the door flew open. <br>
<br>
He turned to look back, having a good idea who it might be. <br>
<br>
Tyl walked in, looked down at the man asleep at her feet, and then to the elf. <br>
<br>
The elf had stared down many opponents, had used people to his own devices many times, and had even left people to their own demise. <br>
<br>
Yet, he paused, and could not move when he saw the tears begin to fall from her eyes. <br>
<br>
What could he say? Nothing seemed right at the moment, and yet, he felt obligated to explain to her, to tell her why he now must leave with the book she seemed to want so badly. <br>
<br>
“I’m…I’m sorry” <br>
<br>
As he said the words, he had to ask himself, why DID she want this book? After learning of its contents, he had to believe it was for personal gain. Fame, fortune, glory? <br>
<br>
His eyes met Tyl’s, as she looked up to regard him, clearly hurt by his betrayal. None of those things seemed to fit what little he knew about this woman, and yet, what else could there be? Confused by her motives, but positive he had the right course in mind, if not for her, or for himself, he steadied his heart. The right course for Hibernia, he told himself. <br>
<br>
“I’m sorry………..but this book must be destroyed.” <br>
<br>
With that, he turned, unable to meet Tyl’s eyes. Best to move on, and get this business over with before he changed his mind. He quietly dropped to the street below, moving amongst the crowd quickly, hoping to find solace in the shadows that were quickly forming as the day expired.<br>
