<br>
<br>
The dawn found the elven rogue sitting beneath a tree outside of Ardee. Having left Tir na Nog underneath the cover of nightfall, the rogue’s black cloak wrapped tight about him for protection from the rain and any prying eyes, he collapsed shortly thereafter at the tree. Yet he could not find any sleep. <br>
<br>
He dared not sleep while the book was in his possession. <br>
<br>
The title seemed harmless enough. Barely legible on the threadbare cover, the words simply read “Beyond the veil, an anthology of the known information about the lands outside our home.” Yet even as he turned the first few pages, the rogue found his heart beating faster; faster than it had while making his escape from the walls of Tir na Nog. <br>
<br>
The first page listed the proclaimed author, Vencklayne. Not many knew of this old elf, but the rogue made it a point to know more than most did. His was only a minor tale in the long, grand history of the elven race. Vencklayne had left the veil, overcome with his own thirst for power. He was quickly considered an outcast, and many had been sent, fearing that in his search for information he may give away the secret of the elven homeland hidden behind the veil. None of those sent had returned. His name soon retreated from the minds of elves, and later from the history books. So it was no surprise that few knew the name today. <br>
<br>
What followed the first page was a series of hand drawn maps. The rogue could only study the first collection in confusion, knowing that he had never seen any of these places before. One page after another was turned in disgust, as the elf was sure he did not know the land they detailed. <br>
<br>
And then he read a word he did know: <br>
<br>
Midgard. <br>
<br>
The first few pages were nothing more than crude sketches of the Midgard frontier, not unlike those he had seen from returning Hibernian rangers. Yet as the pages turned, the maps appeared to be getting closer to the Midgard border. As the rogue turned to the next page, his passive curiosity suddenly became more focused. <br>
<br>
A list of names, ones he could only assume were of towns. Detailed maps, some obviously crafted by midgardians, were included within the book. Although many of the maps were written in a language he did not understand, most of the important words were translated by hand within the book. <br>
<br>
The elf continued to turn the pages, soaking all of the information in. Routes between towns, populations, known military camps, forest trails, and mountain paths; the book contained it all. His eyes grew bigger, his breath stolen away, as he came to a page simply titled “Jordheim”. <br>
<br>
Floor plans, shop locations, guard routes, even hand drawn pictures of the great hall. <br>
<br>
The rogue glanced over his shoulder, the weight of the information in the book weighing heavy on his mind. <br>
<br>
The next page was titled “Albion”, and followed the same course as the maps of Midgard. The elven rogue quickly flipped through, amazed at the splendor of both foreign lands. The collection of maps ended with “Camelot”, though the elf found it interesting that it ended rather abruptly, and certainly not completed. <br>
<br>
Still, with the information detailed within this simple book, the balance between Midgard and Albion could easily be swayed, should the book fall into either of their hands. And should Fagan recover the book, the knowledge could be a rallying point. He could gather a force large enough to overcome either of them, if not both. <br>
<br>
The rogue was pondering this thought, and asking himself if it was altogether a bad outcome, when he came across the next section. An empty page, with the words “Ocean maps” written across the middle. <br>
<br>
What followed was a collection of hand drawn maps, roughly gauging the distance between the realms by way of the oceans. The elf almost dropped the book in shock. Having never traveled on the open seas, he had never thought the realms could be that close to each other. And yet, here was a map that claimed that the ocean could reach each realm easily enough. The rogue wondered where the skills required to sail the open seas could possibly come from, knowing that this was never a prominent skill among the Hibernians. <br>
<br>
And then he spotted it. It was small, and nondescript, but it was obviously an inhabited island. He turned back to the first collection of maps, the ones he did not recognize. Sure enough, a few matched up with the shoreline of the island. He had never heard of this land, yet there it was. <br>
<br>
He then realized the even greater knowledge held within the book. For any realm that could conquer this land, or at least enter into an alliance with those who lived there, would have a platform to launch attacks against the other realms, except this time, by the ocean. <br>
<br>
The war could easily be swayed by such a surprise attack. And having the ability to press a realm on two fronts would win the war in a matter of months. <br>
<br>
The book held the rogue’s interest so tightly that he did not even notice the sun rise above Ardee that day. <br>
<br>
He did not see the town come alive with shopkeepers and weapon smiths preparing for the day’s sales. <br>
<br>
He did not hear the man approach him from behind.<br>
